Two 100 lb. tanks of oxygen - Essential for breathing and immediate survival.
20 liters of water - Critical for hydration and survival over several days.
Portable heating unit - Necessary to maintain body temperature in the moon's extreme temperatures.
Food concentrate - Provides essential sustenance and energy required for the long journey.
Signal flares - Useful for signaling for help or marking the path.
First aid kit, including injection needle - Vital for treating injuries and preventing infections.
Solar-powered FM receiver-transmitter - Important for communication with the mother ship or rescuers.
50 feet of nylon rope - Useful for climbing, securing equipment, or other emergency situations.
Self-inflating life raft - Can serve as an emergency shelter or for carrying supplies.
Parachute silk - Can be used to create shelter, protection from solar radiation, and repair suits or equipment.
Stellar map - Can assist in navigation by identifying constellations and landmarks.
One case of dehydrated milk - Additional nutritional resource but less critical due to the presence of food concentrate.
Two .45 caliber pistols - Limited utility on the moon, though they could potentially be used for signaling.
Box of matches - Largely useless on the moon due to the lack of oxygen for combustion.
Magnetic compass - Useless on the moon due to the lack of a magnetic field.
